The paper deals with source coding, which is a subfield of information theory (cs.IT). It specifically focuses on the vector Gaussian one-helper source-coding problem, which involves compressing a vector source with the help of a helper who has access to the source but cannot communicate directly with the encoder. This problem is relevant to multimedia applications (cs.MM) and signal processing (cs.SI). The paper also mentions lossy vector quantization, which is a technique used in machine learning and data compression (cs.LG). Finally, the paper discusses spatial compression, which is relevant to computer vision and image processing (cs.CV).
